<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>FAN DRIVE CLUTCH: KYSOR 1090 (8000 SERIES) - TROUBLESHOOTING - FAN CONTROL SYSTEM</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="troubleshoot" graphiccount="0">
        <title>FAN CONTROL SYSTEM</title>
        <para>Use the following chart to troubleshoot the fan control system.</para>
        <table id="hl1200102">
            <title>Troubleshooting Chart</title>
            <tgroup cols="3">
                <colspec colnum="1" colname="1" colwidth="2.09in"/>
                <colspec colnum="2" colname="2" colwidth="2.68in"/>
                <colspec colnum="3" colname="3" colwidth="2.09in" colsep="1"/>
                <thead valign="bottom">
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Condition</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Probable Cause</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Remedy</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </thead>
                <tbody valign="top">
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan won't cycle when the air conditioning test is performed.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The outside air temperature is too low, there is a low refrigerant charge or the
                                refrigerant pressure switch is faulty.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the A/C system.</para>
                            <para>Replace the pressure switch if required.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Overtemp warning activates before the fan engages.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Defective overtemp warning switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the overtemp warning switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>The engine appears to overheat. The fan won't engage when the</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The air solenoid valve may be plumbed incorrectly.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the solenoid plumbing. Replumb the valve.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>engine coolant temp gauge is above 195-205&#176;F (91-96&#176;C) or</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The overtemp warning switch is faulty (the warning light activates prematurely).
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the overtemp warning switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>overtemp warning activates before the fan engages.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The overtemp warning switch is too far away from the fan temp switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Move the overtemp warning switch as close to the fan temp switch as possible.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The temp gauge is faulty (reads high).</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the temp switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The fan temp switch is faulty.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the fan temp switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan engages at low engine temperatures while the vehicle is moving.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>A normal condition in extremely hot weather or at low vehicle speeds in warm weather
                                with the A/C on.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>A normal condition.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Faulty temp gauge. (Reads low.)</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the temp sender or gauge.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The A/C system is overcharged or the condenser is covered with debris.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the A/C system.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The refrigerant pressure switch may be faulty.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the pressure switch if necessary.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The fan temperature switch is faulty if the fan engages at low engine temperature and
                                the A/C is off.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the fan temp switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan won't run under any condition.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The wiring may be faulty and/or the temp or freon pressure switch shorted.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the wiring, temp. switch, and freon pressure switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The air solenoid may be faulty. Test the air solenoid valve by shorting across the
                                terminals of the temp switch to energize the air solenoid valve and turn off the fan
                                drive.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>If the solenoid does not activate, replace the solenoid.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan runs continually when the air conditioning is off.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The air solenoid valve may be faulty or plumbed incorrectly.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the air solenoid valve plumbing and replace the valve if faulty.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The air line may be leaking.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the air lines and repair if necessary.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The fan temp switch may be stuck open; with the engine temp below 180&#176;F (82&#176;C)
                                short across the terminals. If the fan turns off, the switch is faulty.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the fan temp switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The pressure switch may be stuck open; turn the A/C system off. If the fan continues
                                to run, short across the pressure switch. If the fan stops, the pressure switch is
                                defective.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the pressure switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>The fan runs continually when the air conditioning is on.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>This is a normal condition in extremely hot weather. To test, spray water on the A/C
                                condenser and the fan should disengage briefly and re-engage when the water evaporates.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>A normal condition in hot weather.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The air conditioning system may be over charged or the condenser covered with debris.
                                Turn the A/C system OFF and if the fan stops, the refrigerant pressure switch is
                                functioning.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Service the A/C system; check the A/C pressure. Check condenser for debris.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The pressure switch may have drifted out of calibration. Use a pressure gauge to
                                compare actual fan on and fan off pressures against the specified pressures.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>If out of calibration, replace the pressure switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan operation is erratic.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Loose electrical connection.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the wiring and repair where necessary.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan temp or pressure switch may be faulty.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>If other system compo-nents check out okay:</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>1. Replace the pressure switch if erratic fan operation associated with the A/C at
                                idle.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>2. Replace the fan temp switch if the erratic operation occurs primarily when the
                                engine is hot.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan frequently cycles when the engine is hot.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>The fan should remain engaged long enough to reduce the temperature 7-10&#176;F (-14
                                to -12&#176;C). The fan switch is defective if the fan disengages after only a 3-4&#176;F
                                (-16 to -15&#176;C) reduction.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Replace the fan temp switch.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan turns on whenever the ignition is on and turns off when the engine is hot.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Air solenoid valve plumbed backwards.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the solenoid installation instructions; plumb correctly.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>If the circuit breaker trips whenever the ignition is turned on, the problem is most
                                likely a fault in the wiring.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Check the wiring and repair where necessary.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>If the circuit breaker trips only when the fan engages, the fault is probably with the
                                solenoid valve.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Use an ohmmeter to check for a shorted solenoid coil. The coil resistance should be
                                greater than 14 ohms. If shorted, replace the air solenoid valve.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Fan frequently cycles when parked with the A/C on.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>This is a normal condition caused by the refrigerant pressure rising to 300 psi with
                                no air flow through the condenser and then dropping below 250 psi when the fan turns on.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>&#160;</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>
